04031nam a22006255i 9780226499888DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264998887 a10.7208/97802264998882doi  a(DE-B1597)521375  a(OCoLC)1029547382  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aB5295b.D54 2018 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a1812231 aDi-Capua, Yoav, eauthor.10aNo Exit :bArab Existentialism, Jean-Paul Sartre, and Decolonization /cYoav Di-Capua. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Visit -- t2. Why Existentialism? -- t3. Commitment -- t4. Meet the State -- t5. Unfreedom's Counterculture -- t6. A Beachhead in the Sixties -- t7. Toward Universal Emancipation -- t8. High Hopes -- t9. Fiasco -- tEpilogue: A Cosmic No Exit -- tNotes -- tSelected Translations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is a curious and relatively little-known fact that for two decades-from the end of World War II until the late 1960s-existentialism's most fertile ground outside of Europe was in the Middle East, and Jean-Paul Sartre was the Arab intelligentsia's uncontested champion. In the Arab world, neither before nor since has another Western intellectual been so widely translated, debated, and celebrated.   By closely following the remarkable career of Arab existentialism, Yoav Di-Capua reconstructs the cosmopolitan milieu of the generation that tried to articulate a political and philosophical vision for an egalitarian postcolonial world. He tells this story by touring a fascinating selection of Arabic and Hebrew archives, including unpublished diaries and interviews. Tragically, the warm and hopeful relationships forged between Arab intellectuals, Sartre, Simone de Beauvoir, and others ended when, on the eve of the 1967 war, Sartre failed to embrace the Palestinian cause. Today, when the prospect of global ethical engagement seems to be slipping ever farther out of reach, No Exit provides a timely, humanistic account of the intellectual hopes, struggles, and victories that shaped the Arab experience of decolonization and a delightfully wide-ranging excavation of existentialism's non-Western history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aDecolonizationzArab countries. 0aExistentialism. 0aPhilosophyzArab countriesy20th century. 4aArab Existentialism. 4aDe-Colonization. 4aExistentialism. 4aGlobal '60s. 4aGlobal Intellectual History. 4aJean-Paul Sartre, Simone de Beauvoir. 4aLutfi al-Khuli. 4aPalestinian Cause. 4aSix-Days War. 4aSuhayl Idris. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226499888423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226499888.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles